Perception&rdquo;, <em>Humanities</em> 3(2): 132&ndash;184.</li>

<li>Thompson, E., 2014, <em>Waking, dreaming, being: Self and
Consciousness in Neuroscience, Meditation, and Philosophy</em>, New
York: Columbia University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2015, &ldquo;Dreamless Sleep, the Embodied
Mind, and Consciousness &ndash; The Relevance of a Classical Indian
Debate to Cognitive Science&rdquo;, in T. Metzinger and J. M. Windt
(eds.), <em>Open MIND</em>, Frankfurt am Main: MIND Group.</li>

<li>Tononi, G., 2008, &ldquo;Consciousness as Integrated Information:
a Provisional Manifesto&rdquo;, <em>Biological Bulletin</em>, 215:
216&ndash;242.</li>

<li>Tuominen, J., Stenberg, T., Revonsuo, A., &amp; Valli, K., 2019,
&ldquo;Social Contents in Dreams: An Empirical Test of the Social
Simulation Theory&rdquo;, <em>Consciousness and Cognition</em>, 69:
133&ndash;145.</li>

<li>Valberg, J.J., 2007, <em>Dream, Death, and the Self</em>,
Princeton &amp; Oxford: Princeton University Press.</li>

<li>Valli, K., 2008, <em>Threat Simulation: The Function of
Dreaming?</em>, Doctoral Thesis, Turku: Annales Universitatis
Turkuensis.</li>

<li>van de Castle, R.L., 1994, <em>Our Dreaming Mind</em>, New York:
Ballantine Books.</li>

<li>van Eeden, F., 1913, &ldquo;A Study of Dreams&rdquo;,
<em>Proceedings of the Society for Psychical Research</em>, 26:
431&ndash;461.</li>

<li>Vold, J.M., 1910/1912, <em>&Uuml;ber den Traum</em>, Vol. I and
II, edited by O. Klemm, Leipzig: Johann Ambrosius Barth.</li>

<li>Voss, U., R. Holzmann, I. Tuin, and J.A. Hobson, 2009,
&ldquo;Lucid Dreaming: A State of Consciousness with Features of Both
Waking and Non-Lucid Dreaming&rdquo;, <em>Sleep</em>, 32(9):
1191&ndash;1200.</li>

<li>Voss, U., K. Schermelleh-Engel, J. Windt, C. Frenzel, and A.
Hobson, 2013, &ldquo;Measuring Consciousness in Dreams: The Lucidity
and Consciousness in Dreams Scale&rdquo;, <em>Consciousness and
Cognition</em>, 22(1): 8&ndash;21.</li>

<li>Voss, U. and A. Hobson, 2015, &ldquo;What Is the State-of-the-Art
on Lucid Dreaming? &ndash; Recent Advances and Questions for Future
Research&rdquo;, in T. Metzinger &amp; J. M. Windt (eds.), <em>Open
MIND</em>, Frankfurt a. MIND Group.</li>

<li>Voss, U., R. Holzmann, A. Hobson, W. Paulus, J. Koppehele-Gossel,
A. Klimke, and M. Nitsche, 2014, &ldquo;Induction of Self Awareness in
Dreams Through Frontal Low Current Stimulation of Gamma
Activity&rdquo;, <em>Nature Neuroscience</em>, 17(6): 810.</li>

<li>Wamsley, E.J., 2013, &ldquo;Dreaming, Waking Conscious Experience,
and the Resting Brain: Report of Subjective Experience as a Tool in
the Cognitive Neurosciences&rdquo;, <em>Frontiers in Psychology</em>,
4, doi:10.3389/fpsyg.2013.00637
 [<a href="http://journal.frontiersin.org/Journal/10.3389/fpsyg.2013.00637/full" target="other">available online</a>]</li>
 
<li>Wamsley, E., C. Donjacour, T. Scammell, G. Lammers, and R.
Stickgold, 2014, &ldquo;Delusional Confusion of Dreaming and Reality
in Narcolepsy&rdquo;, <em>Sleep</em>, 37(2): 419&ndash;422.</li>

<li>Werning, Markus, and Kristina Liefke, 2024, &ldquo;Remembering
Dreams: Parasitic Reference by Minimal Traces in Memories from
Non-Veridical Experiences&rdquo;, in Gregory &amp; Michaelian 2024a,
pp. 119&ndash;154.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2025, &ldquo;Reference in
Memories from Perceptual and Non-Perceptual Experiences: A
Non-Disjunctivist Account Including Vicarious, Oneiric and Fictional
Remembering&rdquo;, <em>Synthese</em>, 205(5): 186. 
doi:10.1007/s11229-025-04936-5</li>

<li>Weygandt, W., 1893, <em>Entstehung der Tr&auml;ume</em>, Leipzig:
Gr&uuml;bel &amp; Sommerlatte.</li>

<li>Williams, B., 1978, <em>Descartes: The Project of Pure
Enquiry</em>, Middlesex: Pelican Books.</li>

<li>Whiteley, Cecily MK, 2021, &ldquo;Aphantasia, Imagination and
Dreaming&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 178(6):
2111&ndash;2132.</li>

<li>Windt, J.M., 2011, &ldquo;Altered Consciousness in
Philosophy&rdquo;, in <em>Altering Consciousness. Multidisciplinary
Perspectives, Volume 1: History, Culture, and the Humanities</em>, E.
Carde&ntilde;a and M. Winkelman (eds.), Santa Barbera, Denver &amp;
Oxford: Praeger, pp. 229&ndash;254.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2013, &ldquo;Reporting Dream Experience:
Why (Not) to Be Skeptical about Dream Reports&rdquo;, <em>Frontiers in
Human Neuroscience</em>, 7. doi:10.3389/fnhum.2013.00708
 [<a href="http://journal.frontiersin.org/Journal/10.3389/fnhum.2013.00708/full" target="other">available online</a>]</li>
 
<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2015a, Dreaming: A Conceptual Framework for
Philosophy of Mind and Empirical Research. Cambridge, MA: MIT
Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2015b, &ldquo;Just in Time &ndash;
Dreamless Sleep Experience as Pure Subjective Temporality&rdquo;, in
T. Metzinger &amp; J.M. Windt (eds.), <em>Open MIND</em>, Frankfurt am
Main: MIND Group.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2018, &ldquo;Predictive Brains, Dreaming
Selves, Sleeping Bodies: How the Analysis of Dream Movement Can Inform
a Theory of Self-and World-Simulation in Dreams&rdquo;,
<em>Synthese</em>, 195(6): 2577&ndash;2625.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2020a, &ldquo;Consciousness in Sleep: How
Findings from Sleep and Dream Research Challenge Our Understanding of
Sleep, Waking, and Consciousness&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy Compass</em>,
15(4): e12661. doi:10.1111/phc3.12661</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2020b, &ldquo;Dreaming: Beyond Imagination
and Perception&rdquo;, in Abraham, Anna, (ed.), <em>The Cambridge
Handbook of the Imagination</em>, Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2021, &ldquo;How Deep Is the Rift Between
Conscious States in Sleep and Wakefulness? Spontaneous Experience Over
the Sleep&ndash;Wake Cycle&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Transactions of
the Royal Society B</em>, 376(1817): 20190696. doi:10.1098/rstb.2019.0696</li>

<li>Windt, J.M. and T. Metzinger, 2007, &ldquo;The Philosophy of
Dreaming and Self-Consciousness: What Happens to the Experiential
Subject during the Dream State?&rdquo;, in Barrett and McNamara 2007c:
193&ndash;248.</li>

<li>Windt, J.M. and V. Noreika, 2011, &ldquo;How to Integrate Dreaming
into a General Theory of Consciousness&mdash;A Critical Review of
Existing Positions and Suggestions for Future Research&rdquo;,
<em>Consciousness and Cognition</em>, 20(4): 1091&ndash;1107.</li>

<li>Windt, J.M., and U. Voss, 2018, &ldquo;Spontaneous Thought,
Insight, and Control in Lucid Dreams&rdquo;, in <em>The Oxford
Handbook of Spontaneous Thought: Mind-Wandering, Creativity, and
Dreaming</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press, pp.
385&ndash;410.</li>

<li>Windt, J.M., T. Nielsen, and E. Thompson, 2016, &ldquo;Does
Consciousness Disappear in Dreamless Sleep?&rdquo;, <em>Trends in
Cognitive Sciences</em>, 20(12): 871&ndash;882.</li>

<li>Wittgenstein, L., 1953, <em>Philosophical Investigations</em>,
G.E.M. Anscombe (ed.), Oxford: Blackwell.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1967, <em>Zettel</em>, G.E.M. Anscombe and
G.H. von Wright (eds.), Berkeley: University of California Press.</li>

<li>Wundt, W.M., 1896, <em>Grundriss der Psychologie</em>, Leipzig:
Engelman; page reference is to the excerpt translated by C.H. Judd,
reprinted in R.L. Woods and H.B. Greenhouse (eds.), <em>The New World
of Dreams</em>, New York: Macmillan (1974), pp. 179&ndash;180.</li>

<li>Zeidman, P., and E. Maguire, 2016, &ldquo;Anterior Hippocampus:
the Anatomy of Perception, Imagination and Episodic Memory&rdquo;,
<em>Nature Reviews Neuroscience</em>, 17(3): 173.</li>

<li>Zeman, Adam, Michaela Dewar, and Sergio Della Sala, 2015,
&ldquo;Lives Without Imagery &ndash; Congenital Aphantasia&rdquo;,
<em>Cortex</em>, 73: 378&ndash;380.</li>

<li>Zeman, Adam ZJ, Michaela T. Dewar, and Sergio Della Sala, 2016,
&ldquo;Reflections on Aphantasia&rdquo;, <em>Cortex</em>, 74:
336&ndash;337.</li>
</ul>

</div> 

